WEBVTT

00:00.531 --> 00:03.602
[Full orchestra plays
<i>Somewhere Over The Rainbow]</i>

00:03.602 --> 00:06.404
Sync and corrections by <font color="#ffff00">APOLLO</font>
<font color="#00ff00"> www.addic7ed.com</font>

00:07.119 --> 00:15.416
♪ Somewhere over the rainbow ♪

00:15.479 --> 00:20.393
♪ way up high ♪

00:20.408 --> 00:25.799
♪ there's a land
that I heard of ♪

00:25.869 --> 00:34.199
♪ Once in a lullaby ♪

00:34.200 --> 00:38.803
♪ Somewhere... ♪
[Cell phone rings]

00:38.804 --> 00:40.539
[Beep] Hey.

00:40.540 --> 00:42.374
Yep.
Where are you?

00:42.375 --> 00:44.676
Yeah, thanks.
That's all we need.

00:44.677 --> 00:47.045
What'd he say?

00:47.046 --> 00:49.481
Uh, yeah, I'm right here.

00:49.482 --> 00:51.239
8:00.
Mm-hmm.

00:55.557 --> 00:57.104
Ivy Lynn.

01:00.150 --> 01:02.509
Hi, you guys.

01:05.631 --> 01:07.132
So...

01:07.133 --> 01:11.562
Do you want the ballad
or the up-tempo first?

01:14.407 --> 01:15.806
They kept me waiting
for almost an hour.

01:15.807 --> 01:17.174
And then
the director took a call

01:17.175 --> 01:18.644
In the middle of my audition.

01:18.645 --> 01:20.712
No. It did not go well.

01:20.713 --> 01:23.048
Is this all the mail?
I was gone a week.

01:23.049 --> 01:25.249
This is all the mail I got?
Oh, I took out the junk mail

01:25.291 --> 01:26.609
and put the magazines
over there.

01:26.631 --> 01:28.099
- So this is the real mail?
- Yeah.

01:28.954 --> 01:31.237
That is so cute...
You took out the junk

01:31.440 --> 01:33.958
And left the real mail.
Where did you hide the tea?

01:33.959 --> 01:35.360
Oh, I rearranged.

01:35.361 --> 01:37.329
There's a tea drawer here.

01:37.336 --> 01:38.903
And there's also macaroni
and cheese and meatloaf

01:38.904 --> 01:40.731
In the oven.
Macaroni and cheese?

01:40.732 --> 01:42.533
You were on a long flight.
I thought, you know,

01:42.534 --> 01:44.203
Coming home to comfort, food
would be nice.

01:44.204 --> 01:46.504
I'm going to go unpack that.
[Coughs]

01:46.505 --> 01:48.639
Can you believe this?
He wants to unpack my suitcase.

01:48.640 --> 01:50.240
You don't have
to unpack his suitcase.

01:50.241 --> 01:51.377
I don't mind.

01:52.612 --> 01:54.379
I have a new assistant,

01:54.380 --> 01:55.681
And he made me
macaroni and cheese.

01:55.682 --> 01:56.981
I'm happy for you.

01:56.982 --> 01:58.716
I'm happy for me too.

01:58.717 --> 02:00.852
- [Chuckles]
- And so cute.

02:00.853 --> 02:02.219
Oh, my God.
[Groans] Straight.

02:02.220 --> 02:04.156
So straight.
You don't know that.

02:04.736 --> 02:06.197
He made a tea drawer.

02:06.659 --> 02:08.258
Did you see this?

02:08.259 --> 02:10.525
They're going ahead
with <i>My Fair Lady?</i>

02:11.163 --> 02:12.430
Derek Wills.

02:12.431 --> 02:14.365
- Oh, God.
- Oh, come on,

02:14.366 --> 02:15.833
You know
he's a terrific director.

02:15.834 --> 02:17.269
Oh, don't even.
I mean,

02:17.270 --> 02:19.337
Don't even!
Oh, oh, sorry, sorry.

02:19.338 --> 02:20.538
Okay.

02:20.539 --> 02:22.607
Revivals and movies.

02:22.608 --> 02:24.742
Why doesn't anyone
do new musicals anymore?

02:24.743 --> 02:27.245
New book, new songs?

02:27.246 --> 02:29.013
We write new musicals.

02:29.014 --> 02:30.416
I thought we were
taking a break.

02:30.417 --> 02:31.883
We are.

02:31.884 --> 02:35.119
I'm just saying,
you know, in general...

02:35.120 --> 02:37.956
Oh, let me get that
out of your way.

02:37.957 --> 02:41.926
- You were looking at that?
- Yeah, I hope that's okay.

02:41.927 --> 02:43.295
Of course, it's okay.
When you houses it for someone,

02:43.296 --> 02:45.006
You're allowed
to read the books.

02:46.298 --> 02:47.799
He likes Marilyn Monroe.

02:48.260 --> 02:49.753
Isn't that interesting?

02:50.803 --> 02:53.538
Poor Marilyn.
So beautiful and tragic.

02:53.539 --> 02:55.439
I think she'd make
a great musical.

02:55.440 --> 02:57.109
- We tried it it was a...
- Both: Huge flop.

02:57.110 --> 02:59.210
Besides, everyone's
doing her now.

02:59.211 --> 03:01.446
There's a Marilyn movie,
diaries.

03:01.447 --> 03:04.322
You know what?
There's an app for the iPad now.

03:05.451 --> 03:07.052
You blow on it
and the skirt goes up.

03:07.053 --> 03:10.221
[Puffs] Goes...
[Laughter]

03:10.222 --> 03:11.788
Doesn't that mean
people like her?

03:11.789 --> 03:13.557
Yes, it means that,
but that doesn't mean

03:13.558 --> 03:15.993
She'd make a good musical.
Well, I like <i>Wicked</i>

03:15.994 --> 03:17.329
and <i>Jersey Boys.</i>
Who'd have thought

03:17.330 --> 03:19.430
Those would be good musicals?

03:19.431 --> 03:20.900
She married Joe Dimaggio.

03:20.901 --> 03:22.501
You could do a baseball number.

03:28.478 --> 03:29.808
I didn't get it.

03:29.809 --> 03:31.477
- I told you already.
- I told my agent

03:31.478 --> 03:34.479
I'm not sexy enough...
I'm the girl next door.

03:34.480 --> 03:36.509
Come hang out with me
at the mayor's office.

03:36.538 --> 03:38.759
You'll be plenty sexy there.
Everyone will stare.

03:38.783 --> 03:39.853
They won't get any work done.

03:39.892 --> 03:41.153
Why do I have to be sexy
all the time?

03:41.191 --> 03:42.908
I wish I was fat.

03:42.988 --> 03:45.657
Plus I'm hungry.
I'm going to start eating more.

03:45.658 --> 03:49.783
- Oh, good. Here.
- Mmm. And plus I'm light.

03:50.129 --> 03:52.329
That's what they keep saying.
"They think that you're light."

03:52.330 --> 03:53.966
Now what does that mean?
That means you're skinny.

03:53.967 --> 03:55.433
- Mmm.
- Karen,

03:55.434 --> 03:57.369
You got two tables up front.
Sorry.

03:57.370 --> 03:59.190
Kiss. Mwah.

04:02.875 --> 04:04.174
[Door clacks shut] I'm home.

04:04.175 --> 04:05.211
- Hey, Hon.
- Hey.

04:05.212 --> 04:06.711
- How's Tom?
- Good.

04:06.712 --> 04:08.480
Hired a new assistant.

04:08.481 --> 04:10.381
Very gung ho.
[Kisses]

04:10.382 --> 04:12.650
Why didn't he pick Tom
up at the airport?

04:12.651 --> 04:14.886
Tom only likes me
to drive him, you know that.

04:14.887 --> 04:16.721
The adoption agency called.

04:16.721 --> 04:18.491
They want to schedule
a time for us to meet

04:18.492 --> 04:21.024
With the social worker.
Isn't that fast?

04:21.026 --> 04:23.329
Thought adoption was slow.
It's like the theater.

04:24.087 --> 04:26.130
Some parts are fast...
Overall it's slow.

04:26.131 --> 04:27.565
Oh, so check it out...

04:27.566 --> 04:31.878
The new assistant boy
had this big idea.

04:32.471 --> 04:34.739
Hey, Leo.
When I say "Marilyn,"

04:34.740 --> 04:36.207
What do you think?

04:36.208 --> 04:38.076
Baltimore.
Baltimore, Maryland.

04:38.077 --> 04:40.645
Um, okay.
Uh, think a person.

04:40.646 --> 04:43.214
Marilyn the person.
Marilyn Manson.

04:43.215 --> 04:44.550
Which would be my point.

04:44.551 --> 04:46.584
Marilyn Monroe.
Who's Marilyn Monroe?

04:46.585 --> 04:50.321
<i>Marilyn... The Musical?
</i> Whoa, whoa, whoa.

04:50.322 --> 04:52.524
You and Tom are taking a break,
I thought.

04:52.525 --> 04:53.757
Uh, I'm not talking about us,

04:53.758 --> 04:55.194
I'm just talking
in the abstract.

04:55.195 --> 04:57.595
You just said
<i>Marilyn... The Musical.</i>

04:57.596 --> 04:59.931
Like,
<i>Marilyn... The Musical.</i>

04:59.932 --> 05:01.532
I didn't say it <i>like</i> anything.

05:01.533 --> 05:03.500
I said it like
it's not a bad idea

05:03.501 --> 05:04.870
If someone were looking
for ideas,

05:04.871 --> 05:06.917
Which you are not.

05:07.273 --> 05:09.706
- Well, how would you do it?
- Oh, for crying out loud.

05:09.707 --> 05:11.341
Don't get mad at me!
You just said that...

05:11.342 --> 05:12.378
I don't know.
You could do scenes

05:12.379 --> 05:13.845
From the movies.

05:13.846 --> 05:15.947
You could have
a big group theater number.

05:16.604 --> 05:18.080
You could have
a baseball number.

05:20.512 --> 05:21.853
That's what Tom said.

05:22.288 --> 05:23.556
That's great mom, I will.

05:23.557 --> 05:25.390
Okay, see you.
Give love to dad.

05:25.391 --> 05:27.392
[Beep]

05:27.393 --> 05:29.126
They're coming to visit
next weekend.

05:29.127 --> 05:30.462
Isn't that great?
It is. I like your parents.

05:30.947 --> 05:32.747
Oh, me too.
I do.

05:32.928 --> 05:34.933
- You worried?
- Me?

05:34.934 --> 05:37.368
No, no. No.
Oh, three nos.

05:37.369 --> 05:39.604
And very high nos.
It's just... come on.

05:39.605 --> 05:40.904
You know they have
a hard time in New York.

05:40.905 --> 05:42.739
- But they want to see you.
- Dev.

05:42.740 --> 05:44.641
The last time they were here,
they spent two days

05:44.642 --> 05:46.610
Trying to convince me
to move back to Iowa.

05:46.611 --> 05:48.581
Yeah, it was a bit
like an intervention.

05:48.582 --> 05:50.248
Totally, ugh.

05:50.249 --> 05:52.249
I'm so looking forward to this.

05:54.000 --> 06:00.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

06:05.264 --> 06:07.732
- What are you doing?
- I'm just...

06:07.733 --> 06:09.901
Just watching a movie.

06:09.902 --> 06:11.237
Well, don't stay up all night.

06:11.238 --> 06:13.386
I won't.

06:18.978 --> 06:20.745
[Over headphones] What's what?

06:20.746 --> 06:22.413
Oh, that.

06:22.414 --> 06:25.016
Just a little going away
present.

06:25.017 --> 06:27.485
Real diamonds.

06:27.486 --> 06:30.021
They must be
worth their weight in gold.

06:30.022 --> 06:32.423
Are you always this generous?

06:32.424 --> 06:37.462
[Pit orchestra plays
jazzy dance music]

06:37.463 --> 06:40.598
♪ ♪

06:40.599 --> 06:42.801
- Hey.
- Hey.

06:42.802 --> 06:44.636
How are you?
I'm sorry.

06:44.637 --> 06:46.437
Hello, hello, hello.
Hey.

06:46.438 --> 06:48.007
- Can I just be right there?
- Sure.

06:48.008 --> 06:50.275
Hi, hi.
Good to see you.

06:50.276 --> 06:52.476
- I'm right here.
- Okay. [Indistinct]

06:57.349 --> 06:58.650
Ivy.
Hi, hi.

06:58.651 --> 07:00.285
Tom!

07:00.286 --> 07:02.052
What are you doing here?
I just got back from London.

07:02.053 --> 07:03.787
Opening up
the West End Production.

07:03.788 --> 07:04.857
Are they as good as us?

07:04.858 --> 07:07.209
- Of course not.
- [Giggles]

07:08.543 --> 07:10.728
- Hey, Tom.
- Hi!

07:10.729 --> 07:12.864
- Dennis.
- I remembered.

07:12.865 --> 07:14.693
No, you didn't.

07:19.166 --> 07:20.744
Did you get it?
[Beep]

07:23.709 --> 07:26.123
Ivy stop,
they fine you for that.

07:27.813 --> 07:30.148
Hey! Hi.
You got by me

07:30.149 --> 07:32.353
So fast downstairs,
I didn't get a chance...

07:33.064 --> 07:34.419
Are you okay?

07:34.420 --> 07:36.144
I'm fine.

07:36.915 --> 07:38.160
What happened?

07:38.224 --> 07:39.426
Nothing. I...

07:40.559 --> 07:41.863
I had an audition this morning.

07:42.473 --> 07:44.095
I didn't get it.

07:44.096 --> 07:47.306
Ivy, you want to leave us?

07:47.700 --> 07:50.502
Oh, Tom,
you know I love the show.

07:50.503 --> 07:51.936
I love you.

07:51.937 --> 07:54.005
The ensemble, not so much?

07:54.920 --> 07:56.357
I just want a part.

07:57.343 --> 07:59.511
I trained.
I'm a trained...

07:59.512 --> 08:01.546
[Music ends, distant applause]

08:01.547 --> 08:03.181
I'm not complaining.

08:04.314 --> 08:05.705
Just dreaming.

08:05.918 --> 08:08.332
Yeah, like everybody.

08:12.525 --> 08:14.692
No, of course, call Ivy.
She'll be great.

08:14.693 --> 08:16.961
You're going to wear that?

08:16.962 --> 08:18.563
Oh, you say that, Tom.

08:18.564 --> 08:20.130
But then you get all...
You get all impatient.

08:20.131 --> 08:21.534
If we don't cut it now,
I'm going

08:21.535 --> 08:23.236
To have to listen
to you whine for weeks.

08:24.002 --> 08:25.805
Then we should do it
because <i>I</i> want to do it.

08:27.493 --> 08:29.274
I want to do it tomorrow.

08:29.603 --> 08:31.665
I will call Ivy.
Bye.

08:32.144 --> 08:34.245
[Beep] He does whine.

08:34.246 --> 08:36.748
I love him, but...
He whines.

08:36.749 --> 08:37.883
You're cutting a demo?

08:37.884 --> 08:39.717
- [Sighs]
- For what?

08:39.717 --> 08:40.953
For the, um...

08:40.953 --> 08:42.754
The Marilyn thing.

08:42.755 --> 08:44.222
You're doing that?

08:44.222 --> 08:45.957
We wrote one song, just to...

08:45.958 --> 08:47.591
- Just to what?
- Well, Tom wanted...

08:47.592 --> 08:49.228
We are in the middle
of an adoption.

08:49.229 --> 08:51.129
Visit from the social worker,

08:51.130 --> 08:53.264
Interviews at the agency,

08:53.265 --> 08:55.234
Criminal checks.
How does writing one song...

08:55.235 --> 08:57.402
You said that you would take

08:57.403 --> 08:59.771
the whole year off
so that we could do this.

09:01.201 --> 09:04.008
- You're so overreacting.
- I'm not overreacting.

09:04.009 --> 09:06.311
When you're in production,
you are never here.

09:06.312 --> 09:08.780
You're out all night.
Leo and I go for days

09:08.781 --> 09:10.482
without seeing you...
Days!

09:10.483 --> 09:12.418
It's not a musical.
It's one song.

09:12.419 --> 09:14.953
Then why can't Tom do it
with someone else?

09:15.539 --> 09:16.914
[Scoffs]

09:20.684 --> 09:22.767
You know what she said
in her last interview?

09:24.094 --> 09:27.141
She said, "please don't make
a joke out of me."

09:28.355 --> 09:29.823
The way they treated her...

09:30.651 --> 09:32.260
That's not even it.

09:33.265 --> 09:35.807
There was just...
There was something about her.

09:36.948 --> 09:39.878
How much she wanted to love
and be loved.

09:39.879 --> 09:41.946
She glows with it.

09:42.376 --> 09:44.063
Reminds me of a saint.

09:47.234 --> 09:49.327
I don't want anyone else
to do her.

09:51.979 --> 09:54.362
I hate the theater,
I really do.

09:54.627 --> 09:56.327
[Footsteps] Leo,

09:56.328 --> 09:57.730
What are you doing home?
It's Tuesday...

09:57.731 --> 09:59.063
You have jazz band.

09:59.064 --> 10:00.499
The social worker
is coming over.

10:00.500 --> 10:02.834
He came home early
so he could meet her...

10:02.835 --> 10:06.137
So <i>we</i> can convince her
that we are a good family.

10:06.138 --> 10:07.805
They don't
let just anybody adopt.

10:07.806 --> 10:09.473
That's what I was trying
to tell you.

10:09.474 --> 10:11.844
I thought maybe you'd want
to change your clothes

10:11.845 --> 10:14.512
So that you could look nice
for the social worker.

10:14.513 --> 10:16.915
[Doorbell rings]
And there she is.

10:16.916 --> 10:18.483
That would be her.

10:18.484 --> 10:20.518
There she is.
Yes.

10:20.519 --> 10:22.922
She's going to like us
no matter what I'm wearing.

10:23.243 --> 10:24.869
And I do want this baby.

10:26.361 --> 10:27.826
I love you both.

10:28.107 --> 10:30.333
We are a fantastic family.

10:30.863 --> 10:32.597
And it's going to be fine.

10:32.598 --> 10:35.566
Yeah, but shouldn't somebody
answer the door?

10:37.369 --> 10:39.704
[Kisses]

10:39.705 --> 10:41.206
- Hi.
- Hi.

10:41.207 --> 10:43.508
- Come on in.
- How are you? Thank you.

10:43.509 --> 10:45.043
- Hello, hello.
- Oh, hi.

10:45.044 --> 10:46.445
- I'm so glad to see you Mrs...
- Mrs. Walters.

10:46.446 --> 10:48.213
- Oh, Rene.
- I am... I'm so sorry,

10:48.214 --> 10:49.613
I'm a little behind today.

10:49.614 --> 10:51.348
I was just going
to run upstairs and change.

10:51.349 --> 10:53.686
Oh, no, no. It's fine.
I know how busy you must be.

10:53.687 --> 10:56.354
I-I saw your play last month...
On Broadway.

10:56.355 --> 11:00.892
I loved it.
Um, can I get you some tea?

11:00.893 --> 11:03.461
- Yes, I-I love tea.
- Sure.

11:03.462 --> 11:05.597
[Sighs] Wow.

11:05.598 --> 11:07.365
- Right this way.
- [Sighs]

11:07.366 --> 11:10.101
[Playing piano introduction]

11:10.102 --> 11:14.072
Both:
♪ as the wise men once wrote ♪

11:14.073 --> 11:19.744
♪ Never give all the heart ♪

11:19.745 --> 11:24.582
♪ Well it's easy to see
he was writing for me ♪

11:24.583 --> 11:29.053
♪ I just wish
I could play that part... ♪

11:29.054 --> 11:30.789
[Door clacks shut]
Oh, I'm sorry I'm late.

11:30.790 --> 11:32.991
We had to have
our birth certificates notarized

11:32.992 --> 11:34.758
For this adoption.
And I couldn't tell them

11:34.759 --> 11:36.593
To hurry it up,
because I didn't want

11:36.594 --> 11:37.830
To get into another fight
with my husband

11:37.831 --> 11:39.631
About <i>Marilyn The Musical,</i>

11:39.632 --> 11:40.964
Since I'm not supposed
to be doing <i>Marilyn The Musical.</i>

11:40.965 --> 11:42.234
Go on, it's sounds amazing.

11:42.235 --> 11:43.902
Well, Ivy is a blinding genius.

11:43.903 --> 11:45.636
It's easy
to make you guys sound good.

11:45.637 --> 11:47.306
Yeah, it's easy
to make us sound bad too.

11:47.307 --> 11:48.710
[Laughs]

11:49.917 --> 11:51.374
Ellis!

11:52.010 --> 11:53.977
Can you please get me some tea?

11:54.408 --> 11:55.862
Sure.

11:58.818 --> 12:00.952
- Oh, you're happy.
- [Laughs]

12:00.953 --> 12:04.255
I'm glad we're doing this.
I really am.

12:04.256 --> 12:06.958
[Kisses]
I've got her in B-flat.

12:06.959 --> 12:08.527
I wanted to keep it
in a Marilyn key.

12:08.528 --> 12:10.829
We weren't sure
how much belt you wanted.

12:10.830 --> 12:13.814
Well, there needs
to be some size at...

12:14.500 --> 12:15.967
♪ From the start... ♪

12:15.968 --> 12:17.470
But it doesn't have
to be a full belt.

12:17.471 --> 12:19.361
It could be a mix.
Okay.

12:20.840 --> 12:22.540
You okay?

12:22.541 --> 12:23.943
Sure.
Why wouldn't I be?

12:23.944 --> 12:26.344
You're sitting up
very straight.

12:26.345 --> 12:28.046
Posture is important to my dad.

12:28.047 --> 12:29.514
He's right.

12:29.515 --> 12:30.816
Looks incredible
when you do that.

12:30.817 --> 12:32.884
Off and running.

12:32.885 --> 12:35.119
- Mom! Hi!
- Sweetie!

12:35.120 --> 12:36.155
Oh, ho.
Dev.

12:36.156 --> 12:38.189
- Roger.
- Daddy.

12:38.190 --> 12:39.492
- Hi, honey.
- So good to see you.

12:39.493 --> 12:40.859
[Indistinct]

12:41.625 --> 12:44.062
Dev, you really
are the handsomest thing.

12:44.063 --> 12:45.464
Why can't you get her
to marry you?

12:45.465 --> 12:47.298
- I'm working on it.
- Okay,

12:47.299 --> 12:48.334
Both of you stop it right now.
Thank you.

12:48.335 --> 12:50.535
So, Dev,

12:50.536 --> 12:53.005
How are things going for you,
down at the mayor's office?

12:53.006 --> 12:55.640
Well, you know,
budgets are still tight.

12:55.641 --> 12:57.342
Municipal government...

12:57.343 --> 12:59.244
[Growls] Thankless job.

12:59.245 --> 13:00.911
No, no, no.
I didn't mean to imply that.

13:00.912 --> 13:03.180
No, new yorkers are so
passionate about their city.

13:03.181 --> 13:05.217
It's really rather inspiring.
Don't get him started.

13:05.218 --> 13:06.584
He loves it down there.

13:06.585 --> 13:07.753
New York is like
the promised land to him.

13:07.754 --> 13:09.554
Yeah, and to you too.

13:10.297 --> 13:12.757
- [Laughs]
- Oh, my goodness.

13:12.758 --> 13:16.060
I'm sorry...
Midwest.

13:16.061 --> 13:17.661
You know,
the prices are different.

13:17.662 --> 13:19.062
But I'm sure the food here

13:19.063 --> 13:21.000
Is delicious.
I'm taking you, mom.

13:21.001 --> 13:23.935
- Oh, that's not necessary.
- I know it's not necessary.

13:23.936 --> 13:25.904
But I want to.
Karen,

13:25.905 --> 13:27.271
We know what kind
of money you make.

13:27.272 --> 13:28.541
You're a waitress.

13:28.542 --> 13:30.842
I'll pay for dinner.

13:30.843 --> 13:32.011
She's an actress,
not a waitress.

13:32.012 --> 13:34.412
You don't have to tell me that.

13:34.413 --> 13:37.048
She did <i>«The Sound Of
Music</i> in high school.

13:37.049 --> 13:40.051
Everybody talked about it
for weeks.

13:40.052 --> 13:44.289
What a voice!
Who knew that meant all this.

13:44.290 --> 13:45.923
Okay, I'm not getting
into this again, dad.

13:45.924 --> 13:47.893
No, sweetie,
we're not getting into anything.

13:47.894 --> 13:49.394
We're just so happy to see you.

13:49.395 --> 13:51.796
I'm happy to see you too.
He worries.

13:51.797 --> 13:52.963
- Mom.
- No, it's so competitive,

13:52.964 --> 13:54.233
And all that rejection,

13:54.234 --> 13:56.568
So we worry,
of course we worry.

13:56.569 --> 13:59.070
Well, sometimes dreams
are hard.

13:59.071 --> 14:01.606
And sometimes, sweetie,

14:01.607 --> 14:06.114
dreams just don't mix
with reality.

14:07.813 --> 14:09.746
That's why
it's so extraordinary

14:09.747 --> 14:11.450
When someone like Karen
follows her heart.

14:11.451 --> 14:13.451
She has so much courage.

14:14.280 --> 14:15.905
I think she's a star.

14:19.825 --> 14:22.894
[Lyrical piano introduction
playing]

14:22.895 --> 14:25.930
[Sultry, as Marilyn Monroe]
♪ as the wise men once wrote ♪

14:25.931 --> 14:31.169
♪ never give all the heart ♪

14:31.170 --> 14:36.307
♪ Well it's easy to see
he was writing for me ♪

14:36.308 --> 14:40.812
♪ I just wish I could play
that part ♪

14:40.813 --> 14:46.117
♪ for the men I have known
who have clearly shown ♪

14:46.118 --> 14:51.156
♪ they've been reading him
from the start ♪

14:51.157 --> 14:54.325
♪ 'Cause when it comes to me ♪

14:54.326 --> 14:57.628
♪ well their kisses come free ♪

14:57.629 --> 15:05.674
♪ but they never
give all the heart ♪

15:13.587 --> 15:15.980
You posted a private
recording session online.

15:15.981 --> 15:17.315
I didn't.

15:17.316 --> 15:18.551
You were the only one
who could have!

15:18.552 --> 15:20.018
This is a disaster.

15:20.019 --> 15:21.020
Michael Riedel's going
to destroy us.

15:21.021 --> 15:22.520
Why? Does he hate you?

15:22.521 --> 15:24.189
Who is he?
He's a Napoleonic

15:24.190 --> 15:25.789
Little Nazi
who works for the post.

15:25.790 --> 15:27.526
- You're fired! Is he fired?
- What?

15:27.527 --> 15:29.661
Yes, he's fired.
You're fired!

15:29.662 --> 15:30.863
I didn't do it.
I just...

15:30.864 --> 15:32.434
I emailed it to my mother.

15:39.034 --> 15:40.437
Wow. It's everywhere.

15:40.710 --> 15:42.407
Those idiotic theater blogs.

15:42.408 --> 15:44.709
I hate everyone
who writes theater blogs.

15:44.710 --> 15:47.077
- Okay, some of it is...
- I don't want to know!

15:49.381 --> 15:51.249
My God, this sucks!

15:51.250 --> 15:52.917
It gets out too fast.

15:52.918 --> 15:54.854
And then everyone just rushes
to judgment

15:54.855 --> 15:57.487
<i>before</i> we even have
a first draft!

15:58.090 --> 15:59.257
Riedel.

15:59.258 --> 16:01.025
[Groans]

16:01.026 --> 16:02.361
Riedel started going
after <i>Spider-Man</i>

16:02.362 --> 16:04.395
Before they even started
previews...

16:04.396 --> 16:05.898
He was already attacking
everyone.

16:05.899 --> 16:08.333
Before they even started
maiming people.

16:08.334 --> 16:11.402
- [Laughs]
- Yeah, I know, I know.

16:11.403 --> 16:12.404
You didn't want me to do it.
And you know,

16:12.405 --> 16:13.738
Fine, you were right.

16:13.739 --> 16:15.773
It's just a complete waste
of time.

16:15.774 --> 16:18.243
- Riedel picked it up.
- Of course he did!

16:18.244 --> 16:19.793
Little creep.

16:20.379 --> 16:22.881
Tom called him
a "Napoleonic Nazi."

16:22.882 --> 16:26.451
He's so right.
[Laughs]

16:26.452 --> 16:29.387
[Laughs] "Napoleonic Nazi."
It's good, right?

16:29.388 --> 16:32.724
No, it's just, uh,
Riedel loves Marilyn.

16:32.725 --> 16:35.393
He's a huge fan of you and Tom.

16:35.394 --> 16:37.796
Thinks <i>Heaven On Earth</i> is
the best musical on Broadway,

16:37.797 --> 16:40.398
In spite of its hideous title.

16:41.534 --> 16:43.651
Thinks the number online is a smash.

16:50.776 --> 16:53.745
You know, he's much smarter
than people give him credit for.

16:53.746 --> 16:55.647
Everyone gets so mad at him,

16:55.648 --> 16:57.804
But... tells the truth.

17:03.389 --> 17:06.590
[Singing along]
♪ for the men I have known ♪

17:06.592 --> 17:09.294
♪ Who have clearly shown ♪

17:09.295 --> 17:13.932
♪ They've been reading him
from the start ♪

17:13.933 --> 17:16.901
♪ 'cause when it comes to me ♪

17:16.902 --> 17:20.571
♪ Well their kisses come free ♪

17:21.237 --> 17:28.449
♪ But they never
give all the heart ♪

17:34.201 --> 17:36.043
This revised agreement
is a joke.

17:38.434 --> 17:40.064
I don't see anybody laughing.

17:40.065 --> 17:42.700
Please, can we please
just try to get through this?

17:42.701 --> 17:44.368
I'm trying to get through this.

17:44.369 --> 17:45.871
But if you're going to be
vindictive about it...

17:46.704 --> 17:49.891
- Vindictive?
- Unrealistic then.

17:51.739 --> 17:53.811
You came into this marriage
with nothing.

17:53.812 --> 17:55.319
Except love.

17:58.094 --> 18:00.918
Bringing up love
at a divorce proceeding

18:00.919 --> 18:02.888
is childish.
Screwing every blonde

18:02.889 --> 18:05.240
who opens her legs for you
is also childish.

18:07.259 --> 18:09.460
I guess that makes
both of us children.

18:09.461 --> 18:10.895
Where are we?

18:10.896 --> 18:12.930
Unless we can come
to an agreement on this,

18:13.313 --> 18:15.933
All assets,
including the company,

18:15.934 --> 18:17.746
Go into escrow immediately.

18:19.405 --> 18:21.939
I have been working
on <i>My Fair Lady</i>

18:21.940 --> 18:24.342
For three years.
Do you really want

18:24.343 --> 18:25.977
to put a bullet in that?

18:25.978 --> 18:28.246
This doesn't have
to destroy everything.

18:28.247 --> 18:29.580
Come on, Jerry.

18:29.581 --> 18:31.807
We had a lot of good years
together.

18:38.138 --> 18:40.193
Is this your version
of begging, Eileen?

18:42.294 --> 18:46.067
Okay.
Everything goes into escrow.

18:48.133 --> 18:50.258
I'll see you in court.

19:04.347 --> 19:06.503
I brought croissants.

19:10.834 --> 19:13.324
I just wanted to let you know
how sorry I am.

19:14.629 --> 19:16.481
I didn't know
what I was doing was...

19:17.853 --> 19:20.252
No. I'm sorry.

19:21.033 --> 19:22.478
I did know it was wrong.

19:23.836 --> 19:25.458
I took the video.
I stole it.

19:25.511 --> 19:26.995
That's exactly what you did.

19:28.741 --> 19:30.709
I was just so excited
to be here...

19:30.710 --> 19:33.578
To be a part of this,
even in such a trivial way.

19:33.579 --> 19:36.047
Not that helping you guys
is trivial.

19:36.048 --> 19:37.982
Far from it.

19:38.318 --> 19:39.715
I just...

19:41.216 --> 19:43.855
In high school, I worked props
for <i>Three On A Match.</i>

19:44.816 --> 19:46.657
That was our first hit.

19:46.658 --> 19:48.392
It wasn't actually a hit.

19:48.393 --> 19:50.027
It had a respectable run.

19:50.028 --> 19:52.363
82 performances!

19:52.364 --> 19:54.031
I felt happy...

19:55.789 --> 19:57.782
Even just being backstage.

19:58.404 --> 20:00.499
I don't know...

20:00.500 --> 20:03.640
I felt... whole.

20:09.581 --> 20:13.017
We've... you know,
we've been working on <i>Marilyn.</i>

20:13.018 --> 20:15.186
- You have?
- Tom.

20:15.726 --> 20:18.723
It's rough, but it'd be great
to have your input.

20:18.724 --> 20:21.592
After all, it was your idea.

20:21.593 --> 20:22.811
Tom!

20:26.866 --> 20:28.374
We have an outline.

20:29.068 --> 20:31.763
And three songs.

20:32.271 --> 20:33.538
We do?

20:33.539 --> 20:37.041
[Plays upbeat jazz tune]

20:37.042 --> 20:39.110
Is that the baseball number?

20:39.111 --> 20:47.085
♪ 'Cause all men like to play
at the national pastime... ♪

20:47.086 --> 20:48.687
[Piano stops]
Give me your cell phone.

20:52.091 --> 20:53.625
[Piano plays upbeat jazz tune
from beginning]

20:53.626 --> 20:55.827
Eileen, we just started
working on this.

20:55.828 --> 20:57.828
Well, that's why I called.
I want this project,

20:57.829 --> 20:59.264
and everyone's going
to think it's too early.

20:59.265 --> 21:00.898
Who do you want to direct?

21:02.102 --> 21:04.802
We're still working on,
um, the songs.

21:04.803 --> 21:06.403
And the book is
all over the place.

21:06.404 --> 21:08.073
Because Derek Wills
is available.

21:08.074 --> 21:11.242
Great! Or I could just
gouge my own eyes out.

21:11.243 --> 21:14.078
Uh, you know, Tom worked
with him a while ago,

21:14.079 --> 21:16.766
And it was
not a great experience.

21:16.782 --> 21:19.082
Oh, we're so hard
on each other in this business.

21:19.083 --> 21:21.253
But let me tell you,
he has mellowed considerably.

21:21.949 --> 21:25.356
He would have had to have
a complete personality change,

21:25.357 --> 21:26.791
as well as a sex change,

21:26.792 --> 21:28.293
for me to even consider it.
[Laughs]

21:28.294 --> 21:30.361
- Well...
- Don't "well."

21:30.362 --> 21:32.295
Oh, don't even "well."
Well, well, what?

21:32.296 --> 21:33.864
Well, he's really talented,
Tom.

21:33.865 --> 21:35.501
You know what?
A lot of people are talented.

21:35.502 --> 21:38.202
We are in an industry
which is lousy with talent.

21:38.203 --> 21:40.204
Is it too much to ask
for kindness too?

21:40.986 --> 21:43.608
Am I a crazy person because
I still expect people to be,

21:43.609 --> 21:46.677
If not lovely, at least civil,
in this terrible business?

21:46.678 --> 21:49.313
Um, let's just have him
take a look at the material.

21:49.314 --> 21:50.848
See if anything sparks.

21:50.849 --> 21:52.684
If it does,
he'll show us one number.

21:52.685 --> 21:54.619
So he'll audition.

21:54.620 --> 21:56.722
- I don't want him to audition.
- So you don't think

21:56.723 --> 21:59.457
It would be fun
to watch Derek crawl?

21:59.458 --> 22:01.526
Yes, actually,
that might be fun.

22:01.527 --> 22:03.495
- I'll give him a call.
- Oh, no, uh,

22:03.496 --> 22:06.898
Eileen, hang on.
Look, we're really flattered.

22:06.899 --> 22:10.902
It's so encouraging
to have someone respond

22:10.903 --> 22:13.204
To... to what we're doing
in such a positive way.

22:13.861 --> 22:15.259
But aren't you...

22:17.643 --> 22:20.478
The word on the street, um...

22:20.479 --> 22:25.183
That your divorce has
complicated things for you

22:25.184 --> 22:26.684
and a lot of your projects.

22:26.685 --> 22:28.586
Oh, Jerry's being Jerry,

22:28.587 --> 22:31.155
And we're going
our separate ways,

22:31.156 --> 22:35.374
but rumors of my death
have been vastly exaggerated.

22:36.495 --> 22:39.397
[Cell phone dials]

22:39.398 --> 22:41.432
<i>Marilyn The Musical...</i>
They've tried it.

22:41.433 --> 22:43.201
It was a huge flop.

22:44.483 --> 22:46.944
I think what we have
will entice you.

22:47.506 --> 22:49.507
I want to do <i>My Fair Lady.</i>

22:50.648 --> 22:54.412
Marilyn was
the American Eliza Doolittle.

22:54.413 --> 22:57.381
And she comes without strings,
unlike <i>My Fair Lady,</i>

22:57.382 --> 22:59.874
which is in escrow
along with my divorce.

23:01.220 --> 23:03.788
Tom Levitt...
He's a nightmare.

23:03.789 --> 23:05.356
Let's just try one number,

23:05.357 --> 23:07.124
see if everyone can get along.
I'm sorry,

23:07.125 --> 23:08.761
They want me to audition?
You've got to be kidding me.

23:08.762 --> 23:11.729
No, they don't want you
at all... I want you.

23:11.730 --> 23:14.699
Eileen, be real.
For me to audition,

23:14.700 --> 23:16.468
Marilyn herself would have
to pop out of that envelope

23:16.469 --> 23:18.469
And do me right here.

23:18.470 --> 23:20.738
Five, six, seven, eight.

23:20.739 --> 23:23.374
[Rehearsal piano playing]

23:23.375 --> 23:24.875
[Piano stops]
Okay, Manuel, right.

23:24.876 --> 23:26.410
You need to get
to this point here

23:26.411 --> 23:28.380
On the beat of the music,
right before she sings.

23:28.381 --> 23:30.381
Hit that clean.
[Door clacks open]

23:30.944 --> 23:32.483
- You ready?
- Yeah, yeah, yeah.

23:32.865 --> 23:34.272
Hang on a sec.

23:37.256 --> 23:38.624
- Hey, darling.
- Hi, love.

23:38.625 --> 23:40.892
[Door clacks shut]
Thanks for doing this.

23:40.893 --> 23:43.628
It's my pleasure.
It's great to see you, Tom.

23:43.629 --> 23:45.394
You look terrific...
Lost some weight.

23:48.634 --> 23:51.669
Okay, so just imagine...
She's in a red dress,

23:51.670 --> 23:53.604
They're in baseball uniforms.

23:53.605 --> 23:54.673
Should we take a look?

23:54.674 --> 23:58.176
[Snappy drum beat introduction]

23:58.177 --> 23:59.178
[Full orchestra accompaniment]
Fellas!

23:59.179 --> 24:00.178
Yeah?

24:00.179 --> 24:01.479
- Fellas!
- Is it?

24:01.480 --> 24:03.281
- Hey, team!
- Off the benches,

24:03.282 --> 24:04.749
it's Marilyn!

24:04.750 --> 24:06.284
♪ I just got a date ♪

24:06.285 --> 24:07.785
♪ She's just got a date ♪

24:07.786 --> 24:09.154
♪ With baseball's Joltin' Joe ♪

24:09.155 --> 24:11.255
- ♪ That lucky so-and-so ♪

24:11.256 --> 24:14.258
♪ So run me 'round the bases
put me through my paces ♪

24:14.259 --> 24:20.465
♪ And teach me all the things
a slugger's lover should know ♪

24:20.466 --> 24:23.167
♪ ♪

24:23.168 --> 24:27.004
♪ What's that there? ♪
♪ that's the pitcher's mound ♪

24:27.005 --> 24:28.705
♪ have you ever seen a shape ♪

24:28.706 --> 24:30.175
♪ That is so perfectly round ♪
♪ batter up ♪

24:30.176 --> 24:32.376
- ♪ play ball ♪
- ♪ You better ♪

24:32.377 --> 24:35.813
♪ Give it your all
'cause all men like to play at ♪

24:35.814 --> 24:39.650
♪ the national pastime ♪

24:39.651 --> 24:41.219
♪ Who's that man? ♪

24:41.220 --> 24:42.719
- ♪ that's the
first-base coach ♪

24:42.720 --> 24:44.323
♪ Have you noticed
that he signals ♪

24:44.324 --> 24:45.957
♪ Every time I approach ♪

24:45.958 --> 24:47.359
- ♪ Kill the ump ♪
- ♪ Throw him out ♪

24:47.360 --> 24:49.827
♪ Because there isn't a doubt ♪

24:49.828 --> 24:52.530
♪ that all men like
to play at ♪

24:52.531 --> 24:58.736
♪ the national pastime ♪

24:58.737 --> 25:02.073
♪ When I was just
a little girl ♪

25:02.074 --> 25:05.743
♪ I liked being dainty
and purty ♪

25:05.744 --> 25:08.846
♪ but now that
I'm giving sports a whirl ♪

25:08.847 --> 25:11.182
♪ I find I kinda like
to get dirty ♪

25:11.183 --> 25:14.685
♪ yeah! ♪

25:14.686 --> 25:16.155
♪ Baby what's that there? ♪

25:16.156 --> 25:18.055
That's the team bull pen.

25:18.056 --> 25:19.358
And I like
the odds I'm seeing...

25:19.359 --> 25:21.325
No girls, all men.

25:21.326 --> 25:22.826
♪ Hit the deck, look alive ♪

25:22.827 --> 25:24.394
♪ beware the lady's
line drive ♪

25:24.395 --> 25:26.365
♪ yes, my skill
and my passion'll ♪

25:26.366 --> 25:28.866
♪ Elevate the national... ♪

25:28.867 --> 25:32.737
[Big band-style interlude]

25:32.738 --> 25:42.380
♪ ♪

25:42.381 --> 25:44.201
Peanuts!

25:45.250 --> 25:47.546
Hot dogs!

25:48.287 --> 25:51.089
Cracker Jack!
I don't care,

25:51.090 --> 25:54.392
I don't care
if I ever get back!

25:54.393 --> 26:05.303
♪ ♪

26:05.304 --> 26:09.073
♪ When the season's over
the play won't end ♪

26:09.074 --> 26:14.045
♪ 'Cause a baseball diamond
is a girl's best friend ♪

26:14.046 --> 26:16.914
♪ Yes her style
and her fashion'll ♪

26:16.915 --> 26:21.152
♪ Elevate the national pastime ♪

26:21.153 --> 26:24.722
♪ ♪

26:24.723 --> 26:26.424
[Applause] Whoo!

26:26.425 --> 26:30.094
That was great!
That was so great!

26:30.095 --> 26:32.663
Wasn't that amazing?
No, it's good.

26:32.664 --> 26:34.999
It's good.

26:35.000 --> 26:36.733
That was great, guys.
Thank you so much.

26:36.734 --> 26:38.335
That was terrific.
Well done, well done.

26:38.336 --> 26:40.572
It was amazing getting
a chance to work with you.

26:40.573 --> 26:42.244
Yeah. Thanks.

26:43.242 --> 26:45.810
- I thought it was great, Ivy.
- [Laughs]

26:45.811 --> 26:47.678
Derek, Derek, thank you.

26:47.679 --> 26:50.181
Thank you so much.
It was, uh, amazing

26:50.182 --> 26:53.351
Just beautiful work.
Sure. Come on.

26:53.352 --> 26:56.254
[Door clacks shut]

26:56.255 --> 26:58.656
- You guys were delicious.
- Thanks.

26:58.657 --> 27:00.624
- Just spectacular.
- Yeah, thanks. So rude.

27:00.625 --> 27:02.325
That's all he said to Ivy,
"yeah, thanks."

27:02.326 --> 27:03.695
- "Thanks" is rude?
- It's the way he said it.

27:03.696 --> 27:05.196
[Mimicking Derek]
"Yeah, thanks."

27:05.197 --> 27:06.298
Well, it's more
than you said to him.

27:06.299 --> 27:07.865
She did us this huge favor.

27:07.866 --> 27:09.433
How much did we pay her
to do all this work?

27:09.434 --> 27:10.934
- Nothing.
- That's right. He can't...

27:10.935 --> 27:12.636
Okay, what did you think
of the work, Tom?

27:12.637 --> 27:14.640
Because I'll tell you,
I thought it was brilliant.

27:15.531 --> 27:17.341
Fine.
It was brilliant.

27:17.342 --> 27:20.478
He did spectacular work
on the song.

27:20.479 --> 27:21.780
I've already conceded
that the work is brilliant.

27:21.781 --> 27:23.981
So what?
So what?

27:23.982 --> 27:25.851
Julia, please,
I love this project.

27:25.852 --> 27:27.718
I love you.
I just don't want

27:27.719 --> 27:29.687
to put it or you or me

27:29.688 --> 27:32.023
In danger.
How is it dangerous?

27:32.024 --> 27:34.492
You know the history.
I am not making this up.

27:35.446 --> 27:37.670
He is a terrible human being!

27:41.154 --> 27:43.701
- The guy's a nightmare.
- There is a certain lack

27:43.702 --> 27:45.698
Of chemistry
between you and Tom.

27:45.715 --> 27:48.114
All that fawning
